Real-World Example: ATM Withdrawal
Suppose a developer is coding an ATM application.
1. Error (Human Mistake)
The developer writes:
Java
if(balance > amount)
instead of:
Java
if(balance >= amount)
The developer forgot to allow withdrawal when the balance is exactly equal to the withdrawal amount.
➡️ This human mistake is called an Error.
2. Bug (Defect)
Because of the mistake, the ATM software contains a defect:
Account balance = ₹5,000
Withdrawal amount = ₹5,000
The software incorrectly rejects the transaction.
➡️ This defect in the software is called a Bug.
3. Failure
A customer with exactly ₹5,000 in their account tries to withdraw ₹5,000.
Expected result:
Withdrawal should succeed.
Actual result:
ATM displays "Insufficient Balance".
➡️ The incorrect behavior seen by the customer is called a Failure.
One-Line Interview Answer
Developer mistake → Error
Defect in software → Bug
Incorrect behavior seen by user → Failure
ATM Example: Wrong condition in code (Error) → defect in withdrawal logic (Bug) → customer cannot withdraw money even with sufficient balance (Failure).
